j": "gene", "prob": 0.9965231418609619, "span": {"begin": 699, "end": 706}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:3130"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HLA-DQ8", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9954354763031006, "span": {"begin": 713, "end": 720}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:100507436"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HLA-peptide complexes", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9669317007064819, "span": {"begin": 727, "end": 748}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "antigen presenting cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.835935652256012, "span": {"begin": 796, "end": 820}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "T cells", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5751885175704956, "span": {"begin": 854, "end": 861}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:445347"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "T cell receptors", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.974208414554596, "span": {"begin": 873, "end": 889}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "HLA", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.5799180269241333, "span": {"begin": 907, "end": 910}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:81669"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "HLA-", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9939764738082886, "span": {"begin": 907, "end": 911}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "gluten", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.4896526634693146, "span": {"begin": 1052, "end": 1058}}], "text": "For the initiation of adaptive responses, the cellular components required need to be simultaneously present in lymphoid structures present in the target tissue/organ. In the case of the gastrointestinal system these lymphoid structures are the Peyer&rsquo;s patches and the mesenteric lymph nodes. The relevant cellular components are professional antigen presenting cells like dendritic cells, antigen specific B cells and T cells expressing gluten-reactive T cell receptors. Both dendritic cells and antigen specific B cells can endocytose and degrade complex antigens, resulting in peptides of variable length. Upon intracellular binding of such peptide antigens to HLA-class II molecules, like HLA-DQ2.5 and HLA-DQ8, such HLA-peptide complexes will be transported to the cell surface of the antigen presenting cells, where they can be recognized by T cells expressing T cell receptors specific for the HLA-peptide complex. Thus, once all relevant cellular components are present in the lymphoid structures, the stage is set for the induction of a gluten-specific T cell response.", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 22:00:04 +0000 2026"}